The actual bug
.includes(keyword) is a raw substring match, not a word match. That means it fires on any word that contains the keyword as a fragment, even inside a completely unrelated word. This is exactly your "bounces to another topic" symptom:
Customer saysContains substringWrongly routes to finance"Can you relate that to last month?"late✅ triggers overdue/late"That's my collateral for the loan"late✅"We need to escalate this"late✅"Put it on the billboard"bill✅"That's a billion-dollar market"bill✅"Give me a summary of the meeting" (a generic ask, not financial)summary✅
So the second any of these substrings shows up — regardless of context, regardless of which agent is currently active — the caller gets yanked into the finance agent talking about invoices. That's your "confuse/bounce back" bug exactly.
There's a second, related problem: this function only checks one agent in isolation. Nothing here compares against sales/marketing keyword scores or considers who's currently speaking, so there's no way to prefer "stay on the current topic" over "jump because one word matched."
The fix
1. Use word-boundary matching, not substring matching:Created a file, read a fileCreated a file, read a file2. The bigger structural fix you actually need
Word-boundary matching stops the worst false positives, but the real fix is architectural. Right now each agent (finance, sales, marketing) almost certainly has its own routeToXAgent(intent): boolean checked independently. That means:

Two agents can both return true for the same sentence, and whichever gets checked first silently wins
There's no "stickiness" — if the caller is already mid-conversation with the finance agent, a single stray word can still yank them to another agent even mid-sentence

What you want in your orchestrator (likely in agent-voice/src/server.ts, which is the file I still can't see in full) is something like:
tsconst scores = {
  finance: scoreFinanceIntent(transcript),
  sales: scoreSalesIntent(transcript),
  marketing: scoreMarketingIntent(transcript),
};

const currentAgent = session.activeAgent; // whoever is currently talking
const currentScore = scores[currentAgent] ?? 0;
const [bestAgent, bestScore] = Object.entries(scores).sort((a, b) => b[1] - a[1])[0];

// Require a clear margin to switch agents mid-call — this is what stops
// single-keyword "bounce back" glitches.
const SWITCH_THRESHOLD = 0.6;
const SWITCH_MARGIN = 0.25;

if (bestAgent !== currentAgent && bestScore >= SWITCH_THRESHOLD && (bestScore - currentScore) >= SWITCH_MARGIN) {
  session.activeAgent = bestAgent;
}
This gives you two protections your current code has neither of:

Comparison across agents instead of "first match wins"
Hysteresis/stickiness — a topic switch only happens when the new agent's confidence clearly beats the current one, not on any single keyword hit

